WEBVTT

00:00:01.769 --> 00:00:05.795
Joe Dolson: Welcome
to WordPress Accessibility Day 2025.

00:00:06.389 --> 00:00:10.140
I'm Joe Dolson, a lead organizer
of WordPress Accessibility Day

00:00:10.159 --> 00:00:11.168
and a board member

00:00:11.169 --> 00:00:13.939
of the WP Accessibility Day
non-profit organization

00:00:14.329 --> 00:00:16.350
along with Bet Hannon
and Amber Hinds.

00:00:17.070 --> 00:00:19.289
I'm also a member
of the WordPress Accessibility Team

00:00:19.289 --> 00:00:22.139
and a core committer
on the WordPress Open Source Project.

00:00:22.949 --> 00:00:26.190
This is
our fifth WordPress Accessibility Day

00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:28.990
and we're pretty excited
about what's coming up.

00:00:29.010 --> 00:00:32.070
It's truly amazing to see
how much this event has changed

00:00:32.459 --> 00:00:35.884
since the WordPress Accessibility Team
founded it in 2020.

00:00:36.630 --> 00:00:40.949
We've got 28 speakers this year
with 28 unique perspectives

00:00:40.950 --> 00:00:44.050
on the user experience for people
with disabilities on the web.

00:00:44.310 --> 00:00:48.569
Our speakers represent 11 countries
and 10 time zones making this event

00:00:48.570 --> 00:00:49.570
truly global.

00:00:50.100 --> 00:00:53.450
A quarter of our speakers self-identify
as living with a disability.

00:00:54.149 --> 00:00:58.408
This year's sessions cover
an enormous range of topics from coping

00:00:58.409 --> 00:01:00.542
with irregular
and unpredictable bandwidth,

00:01:00.734 --> 00:01:02.789
to developing with continuous testing,

00:01:03.240 --> 00:01:05.240
to the accessibility of physical events.

00:01:05.699 --> 00:01:09.149
There are topics at every level
and we hope you're all able to take

00:01:09.150 --> 00:01:11.406
something with you from this event
that you can apply

00:01:11.406 --> 00:01:13.949
in your everyday work on or off the web.

00:01:14.909 --> 00:01:16.050
As of this moment,

00:01:16.499 --> 00:01:22.799
we have 2,097 attendees
registered to attend.

00:01:23.369 --> 00:01:26.159
That's an incredible response
and we're amazed by your excitement

00:01:26.159 --> 00:01:27.859
about WordPress and accessibility.

00:01:28.650 --> 00:01:32.459
This event wouldn't be possible
without our amazing team of organizers

00:01:32.850 --> 00:01:34.950
and the generous support of our sponsors.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.910
This year's organizing team
included almost 30 people

00:01:39.810 --> 00:01:42.328
and there are
about an additional 30 volunteers

00:01:42.329 --> 00:01:44.789
helping out today to make
this event run smoothly.

00:01:45.630 --> 00:01:48.880
I'd be remiss if I didn't make
a point of thanking our team leads.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:51.600
Bet Hannon, sponsors and finance,

00:01:52.229 --> 00:01:56.940
Adrian Grace, volunteers team,
Isla Waite, technology and vendors,

00:01:57.479 --> 00:02:00.120
June Liu and Michelle Frechette,
marketing,

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:02.579
Joni Halabi, translations,

00:02:02.699 --> 00:02:06.059
Ricky Blacker, post-event issues,

00:02:06.570 --> 00:02:07.570
Ricky Onsman,

00:02:07.649 --> 00:02:08.939
Asia Pacific liaison,

00:02:09.270 --> 00:02:11.009
and Ryan Bracey, speakers,

00:02:11.549 --> 00:02:12.748
and Amber Hinds,

00:02:12.749 --> 00:02:15.598
who isn't leading a specific team
for the first time

00:02:15.599 --> 00:02:19.529
